```

## Follow-up Questions
What's the memory impact of closures? How do they relate to garbage collection? Can you explain closure optimization?

## Scoping Differences
`var` is function-scoped and accessible throughout the entire function, regardless of block boundaries. `let` and `const` are block-scoped, limited to `{}` blocks, loops, and conditionals.

## Temporal Dead Zone
`let` and `const` exist in their scope from the start but can't be accessed until declared - this is the temporal dead zone. `var` is hoisted and initialized as `undefined`.

## Practical Examples
```javascript
// var - function scoped
function test() {
  if (true) {
    var x = 1;
  }
  console.log(x); // 1 - accessible outside block
}

// let/const - block scoped
function test() {
  if (true) {
    let y = 1;
  }
  console.log(y); // ReferenceError - not accessible
}

// Temporal dead zone
console.log(z); // undefined (var)
var z = 1;

console.log(w); // ReferenceError (let)
let w = 1;

// Common TDZ errors
function tdzExample() {
  // console.log(myVar); // ReferenceError: Cannot access 'myVar' before initialization
  let myVar = 5;
  console.log(myVar); // 5
}

// Loop closures with var (classic bug)
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); // 3, 3, 3 (same i reference)
}

// Loop closures with let (correct behavior)
for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(j), 100); // 0, 1, 2 (each j is block-scoped)
}

// const reassignment rules
const obj = { name: 'John' };
obj.name = 'Jane'; // ✅ Object property can be modified
obj = { name: 'Bob' }; // ❌ TypeError: Assignment to constant variable

const arr = [1, 2, 3];
arr.push(4); // ✅ Array methods work
arr = [5, 6]; // ❌ Cannot reassign array reference
```

## Global Object Differences
```javascript
var globalVar = 'var global';
let globalLet = 'let global';
const globalConst = 'const global';

console.log(window.globalVar); // 'var global' - becomes property of window
console.log(window.globalLet); // undefined - not a window property
console.log(window.globalConst); // undefined - not a window property
```

## Common Pitfalls
- `var` in loops creates a single shared variable reference
- `const` objects and arrays can still have contents modified
- Accessing `let/const` before declaration throws `ReferenceError`
- `var` declarations can be redeclared in same scope, causing confusion

## Best Practices
Use `const` by default for immutability, `let` only when reassignment is necessary, and avoid `var` entirely in modern JavaScript to prevent scope-related bugs and write more predictable code.

