## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design a small data-layer primitive using closures, promises, and batching for performance.

## Key Concepts
- Closures and per-key caches
- Promise queuing and batch network calls
- TTL-based eviction and memory safety
- Error handling and cancellation tokens

## Code Example
```javascript
function createBatchingCache(fetcher, { batchDelay = 100, ttl = 5000 } = {}) {
  const cache = new Map(); // key -> { value, expiresAt }
  const inFlight = new Map(); // key -> { promise, resolve, reject }
  let batch = [];
  let timer = null;

  async function flush() {
    const keys = batch;
    batch = [];
    const uniq = Array.from(new Set(keys));
    try {
      const results = await fetcher(uniq);
      uniq.forEach((k, i) => {
        const v = results[i];
        cache.set(k, { value: v, expiresAt: Date.now() + ttl });
        if (inFlight.has(k)) inFlight.get(k).resolve(v);
        inFlight.delete(k);
      });
    } catch (e) {
      uniq.forEach(k => inFlight.get(k)?.reject(e));
      uniq.forEach(k => inFlight.delete(k));
    }
  }

  return {
    get(key) {
      const c = cache.get(key);
      if (c && c.expiresAt > Date.now()) return Promise.resolve(c.value);
      if (inFlight.has(key)) return inFlight.get(key).promise;
      let resolve, reject;
      const p = new Promise((res, rej) => { resolve = res; reject = rej; });
      inFlight.set(key, { promise: p, resolve, reject });
      batch.push(key);
      if (!timer) timer = setTimeout(() => { timer = null; flush(); }, batchDelay);
      return p;
    },
    clear() {
      cache.clear();
      inFlight.clear();
      batch = [];
      if (timer) clearTimeout(timer);
      timer = null;
    }
  };
}
```

## Why This Is Asked
